<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <!--
    macOS TCC ("Files and Folders") usage descriptions. This app is NOT
    sandboxed (see Entitlements.plist), so saving an email attachment into a
    protected user folder requires these keys: macOS shows the string in the
    permission prompt the first time we write there, and grants access once the
    user approves. Without them the write is silently denied and the save fails.
    Tauri merges this file into the generated macOS bundle Info.plist.
    These only prompt on a real user-initiated save, never at launch.
  -->
  <key>NSDownloadsFolderUsageDescription</key>
  <string>Forward Email needs access to your Downloads folder to save email attachments there.</string>
  <key>NSDocumentsFolderUsageDescription</key>
  <string>Forward Email needs access to your Documents folder to save email attachments there.</string>
  <key>NSDesktopFolderUsageDescription</key>
  <string>Forward Email needs access to your Desktop folder to save email attachments there.</string>

  <!--
    Disable App Nap. When the window sits on a background Space (Mission
    Control desktop), macOS naps the app and WebKit suspends the WKWebView's
    WebContent process; on return the page is re-rendered/re-fetched, which the
    user sees as a ~1-2s blank reload. Keeping the app out of App Nap lets the
    web content (and the existing background mail sync) stay resident.

    Tradeoff: slightly higher background CPU/battery use while occluded — usually
    acceptable for a mail client that already syncs in the background.

    NOTE: App Nap only applies to a built/notarized .app bundle, not `tauri dev`.
    Verify with `pnpm tauri:build`, then put the app on a dedicated Space and
    switch away/back. If this alone doesn't stop the reload, the WebContent
    process is being jettisoned independently and we escalate to native objc2
    (hold an NSProcessInfo activity assertion and/or set the WKWebView's native
    background so any discard shows the theme colour, not white).
  -->
  <key>NSAppSleepDisabled</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
